    type: "rrb_ntpc",
    language: "english",
    text: "The gig economy, characterized by short-term contracts, freelance work, and on-demand labor facilitated by digital platforms, has grown rapidly in recent years, with millions of workers in countries including India participating as delivery workers, ride-hailing drivers, freelance professionals, and providers of various services through platforms like Swiggy, Zomato, Ola, Uber, Urban Company, and Upwork. The growth of gig work has been facilitated by smartphone penetration, reliable mobile internet, digital payment infrastructure, and the development of algorithmic platforms that efficiently match demand for services with supply of labor, creating new economic opportunities for people who lack the formal credentials or social connections required for traditional employment. Workers in the gig economy often value the flexibility to choose their own working hours, to combine gig work with other income sources or family responsibilities, and to avoid the constraints of a conventional employer-employee relationship, and for some highly skilled freelance professionals the gig economy provides significantly higher income than conventional employment. However, gig workers typically lack the social protections associated with formal employment including guaranteed minimum wages, paid leave, health insurance, workplace injury compensation, and pension contributions, leaving them economically vulnerable during periods of illness, slow demand, or when platforms change their algorithms or commission structures in ways that reduce earnings. The appropriate legal classification of gig workers as employees entitled to labor protections or as independent contractors who bear the risks of self-employment, and the design of social protection systems that can cover workers in non-standard employment arrangements, are among the most contested labor policy questions of the present era."
