    text: "The Amazon river, the world's largest river by discharge volume, carrying approximately twenty percent of all fresh water that flows into the world's oceans, begins its journey in the Andes Mountains of Peru and flows approximately six thousand four hundred kilometres eastward across the South American continent before emptying into the Atlantic Ocean, draining a basin of approximately seven million square kilometres that encompasses parts of nine countries. The immense volume of fresh water discharged by the Amazon creates a zone of freshwater in the Atlantic Ocean that extends hundreds of kilometres from the river's mouth, and the river's nutrient-rich waters fertilize the open ocean and support extraordinary marine productivity in the surrounding waters. The Amazon river basin contains approximately ten percent of all species on Earth and is home to approximately thirty million people including more than three hundred and fifty indigenous groups, many of whom have inhabited the forest for thousands of years and whose traditional knowledge of the ecosystem and its plants and animals is of incalculable scientific and cultural value. The river is navigable for ocean-going vessels approximately three thousand seven hundred kilometres inland to the city of Iquitos in Peru, making it a critical transportation artery for the remote communities of the Amazon basin that lack road connections, and the river and its tributaries serve as highways for commerce, travel, and the movement of goods throughout the region. Rising temperatures and changing precipitation patterns associated with climate change, combined with deforestation that reduces the local water cycle, are beginning to affect the hydrology of the Amazon basin, with more frequent and severe droughts threatening the river's ecology and the livelihoods of the people who depend on it."
